Ad-hominem: Ugly people have ugly thoughts, that's basically the gist of physiognomy. Evil people will produce evil ideas and a frog will always croak and never bark. Instead of bothering to engage with the arguments of a demon tell him: "You are a demon and all you say are lies"

Slippery slope: Evil invites more evil and rotting creates more rot. The Overton window is very much real and constantly moving.
 "We never eat salt in this village" "Salt is good on potatoes" "Salt improves all meals" "Salt is good" "Salt the waters and the ground"

No true scotsman: If all other scots drink whiskey, play golf and wear kilts, but Angus does not, is he truly scottish? Is he really a scotsman if he lacks all the properties of one? And if Jack is English but does all of the above isn't he more scottish than he is English?

Anecdotal: The fact that something is anecdotal means no less than if it was observed by science. Ball lighting does not exists according to science, but it is very much real, though unobserved in a lab. So is God. All data is anecdotal.
Black-or-white: Even though three alternatives exist, that does not mean that all of them are different colours - two of them are black and one is white. There are many lies and only one true truth.

Loaded question: You can always reply in a way that's truthful:
"Still having problems with your venereal disease?" 
"Of course not, because I have never had a venereal disease!"

"Does this dress make me look more fat?"
"You are always beautiful"

False cause: The fact that there is no obvious link between the two does not mean they are not connected. This attempt at mockery of correlation/causation forgets that both the high divorce rate and margarine are products of modern day's decay.
